WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.520
Hi, I'm so pleased to be here at the virtual day for USAR this year to give

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:12.160
you a first look at Positron. My name is Julia Silge and I have been working in

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:16.980
data science for about the last 10 years, for about the last 5 years as largely a

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:23.680
tool builder for building tools for other data scientists to use. I work at

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:30.040
PositPBC these days, formerly known as rstudio, and there I worked on R

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:36.360
packages for machine learning and modeling, R and Python packages for ML

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:42.080
Ops, but for about the last two years I have been working on Positron, which is

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:46.959
this new next-generation IDE for data science that I'm excited to get to give

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:52.400
you a glimpse of today. That's a little bit about me and I'm gonna say kind of

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:57.040
what I think you are like so that you can understand the perspective which I

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:01.840
am speaking here about Positron. I'm assuming you are an R user, you have

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:08.959
probably used rstudio, perhaps you have dabbled in another editor or IDE, but I'm

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:16.320
assuming that largely most of your R usage happened in rstudio. So let's dig

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:23.760
into Positron. Positron is a new next-generation data science IDE. It's

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:28.080
been available for a beta testing for about the last year and just this summer

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:34.800
Positron has moved to stable releases, so out of our beta period. It's an IDE, which

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:39.239
stands for integrated development environment, and that's a piece of

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:45.199
software that allows you as a user to yourself develop software. So this

00:01:45.279 --> 00:01:50.400
example, this screenshot, shows someone using Positron together with Cordo.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:57.040
They're writing a report in Cordo using R and you can see the source code on one

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:01.760
side and then the rendered report over on the other side. So this is an IDE.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:06.519
There's a ton of IDEs out there in the world and over the course of this talk I

00:02:06.519 --> 00:02:12.559
want to tell you what's new and or different and or special about Positron

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:18.479
so you can understand why we're building it, how an R user should think

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:23.440
about Positron compared to the other options that are out there for you, and

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:28.039
whether it might be a good fit for you or whether it's something you don't need

00:02:28.039 --> 00:02:34.039
to worry about. The first thing I want to emphasize is that Positron is an IDE

00:02:34.039 --> 00:02:39.919
specifically for doing data science. So at the company where I work at Posit, we

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:46.039
have extensive domain knowledge in data science tooling. We know that someone

00:02:46.039 --> 00:02:53.160
who is writing code for data analysis or data science or machine learning, that

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:58.320
person is different from someone who is writing general-purpose code like

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:04.279
writing code for a website or a mobile app or something. We're huge proponents

00:03:04.279 --> 00:03:09.639
of code first data science as opposed to, you know, pointy clicky kinds of tools

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:15.919
but tools that are built for a typical software engineer who is writing code

00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:20.360
for, you know, some sort of general purpose, those kinds of tools are

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:26.240
often not a good fit for someone who is writing code to analyze data. So all

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:31.279
across our org, pretty much every single thing we make or do or build is informed

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:37.320
by how how deeply we know and believe in these things that the code first data

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:41.360
science and also people who are doing data science are different from software

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:47.000
engineers. So we believe by thinking about these two things, we can make you

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.479
as a data practitioner more productive by building tools that are specifically

00:03:51.479 --> 00:03:56.000
for you and the kind of tasks you need to do. And that's exactly why we're

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
building Positron, this new IDE. There isn't something quite like Positron

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:07.199
out there which is one platform where you can do all of your data science. So

00:04:07.199 --> 00:04:11.119
that's the first thing. The second thing I want to tell you is that Positron is

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:17.040
a polyglot or multilingual IDE. It's currently built today with support for

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:22.480
both R and for Python. A lot of environments that are built that are

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:27.839
specifically built for data analysis are built to use one language for

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:32.799
scientific computing. Tools you may have heard about or use yourself that fall

00:04:32.799 --> 00:04:39.480
into this category include RStudio, include MATLAB. There's a lot of these

00:04:39.480 --> 00:04:44.440
where the environment is built just to use one language for scientific

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:49.839
computing. These of course are tools people are hugely productive with, but

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:56.320
there also are limits to these kinds of tools or IDEs, especially for that

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:01.519
proportion of people who use multiple languages for data science. This can

00:05:01.519 --> 00:05:05.959
happen literally on the same project. Your project can combine two

00:05:05.959 --> 00:05:11.160
languages. It can happen over the span of a week or weeks as you move from one

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:15.440
project to another that may use different languages. Almost certainly

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:19.559
it's going to happen over the span of your career. I know this has been true

00:05:19.559 --> 00:05:24.359
for me in my career that I have used different languages over my

00:05:24.359 --> 00:05:32.399
professional life, and it's true for most of us. I know many of you are

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:38.040
already familiar with this. You do things like build R packages that have C

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:43.760
code in them, or you build complex shiny apps and so you both write R and

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:49.119
JavaScript, or maybe you are someone who uses R in addition to Python. By

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:54.920
contrast, with the IDEs or editors that are built for one language, Positron is

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:59.559
built with front-end user-facing features that are about the tasks you

00:05:59.559 --> 00:06:03.640
need to do when you're analyzing data and doing other data-specific kind of

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:09.040
work, and then back-end language packs that provide the engines for all of

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:14.000
those features and tasks. In this screenshot, you see that. You see a

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.239
console for iterative running of code. You see a place for your plots, a place

00:06:20.239 --> 00:06:24.880
for your variables, a place in addition to where you're actually editing your

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:30.480
main source code here. You'll notice that this is all running on Python,

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:35.160
though, not on R. Even though it looks a lot like RStudio, it's running

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:40.920
Python. If you are someone who uses more than one language in your day-to-day

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:47.480
work, then Positron is built with you and your needs in mind. One of the big

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:51.959
investments we needed to make in order to build Positron was new modern

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:57.480
language tooling for R. Positron has a brand new Jupyter kernel for R that's

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:04.160
called Arc. A Jupyter kernel is software that provides R a way to

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:09.359
talk back and forth with a front-end. If you hear Jupyter kernel, you might think

00:07:09.399 --> 00:07:14.799
Jupyter Notebook. In that case, that is an example of a front-end, but how we

00:07:14.799 --> 00:07:19.839
use it in Positron is that Positron as a whole is the front-end. The kernel

00:07:19.839 --> 00:07:26.640
allows the back-end language runtime, R, to talk back and forth so that the

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:31.000
front-end knows what to do when R does something there. It gives you things

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:37.600
like completions, diagnostics, debugging, just a ton of features that improve

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:42.160
the experience of writing R code. In this screenshot, I've got one of the R

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:46.799
packages that I maintain up here, and this is showing me debugging the

00:07:46.799 --> 00:07:51.440
function that I wrote in the R package. This is possible because of

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:56.559
this new modern language tooling for R that we've been able to invest in.

00:07:56.559 --> 00:08:01.239
The exciting thing is that it is a Jupyter kernel, so it can be used anywhere a

00:08:01.239 --> 00:08:05.399
Jupyter kernel can be used. The Positron team has also built a new

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:11.119
formatter for R that's called AIR. These are both examples of how the

00:08:11.119 --> 00:08:18.559
architectural decisions around Positron let us build modular, reusable pieces of

00:08:18.559 --> 00:08:23.519
modern language tooling that can be used in multiple contexts. AIR is

00:08:23.519 --> 00:08:26.920
really interesting because it works great in Positron, but it also works

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:31.359
great in RStudio. It also works great in VS Code. It also works great from the

00:08:31.359 --> 00:08:36.960
command line. It's exciting to me as someone who loves R to see how the

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:41.679
architectural decisions we've made allow us to bring things to the whole R

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:47.039
community. To learn more about AIR, I would draw your attention to another

00:08:47.039 --> 00:08:54.080
useR! talk happening in person on August 10th by my co-workers Lionel, Henry, and

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:58.960
Davis Vaughn. The third thing I want to highlight about Positron is that it is

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:03.840
both familiar and extensible. It's familiar to many of you who are

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:08.239
watching this video because it is inspired pretty directly by RStudio.

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:13.479
Many of the people working on Positron right now are the same exact people who

00:09:13.479 --> 00:09:18.280
have worked on RStudio. Here you see what that means. This is a

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:23.719
very RStudio-like interface where you see a console, you see a source editor,

00:09:23.719 --> 00:09:29.719
you see a very interactive help pane, but it's being used with Python instead

00:09:29.719 --> 00:09:35.039
of with R. If you are someone who has wanted to work with Python and just

00:09:35.039 --> 00:09:38.760
always felt like, I wish I had something like RStudio, then this is great

00:09:38.760 --> 00:09:44.239
news for you. However, for some of you, this may bring up feelings of concern, of

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:49.679
anxiety. You may be curious about what is happening to RStudio. RStudio

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:57.119
is incredibly stable, solid software. It has well over a decade, I

00:09:57.119 --> 00:10:03.760
believe well over 15 years actually, of real-world use on it. It is true that as

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:09.880
of today, Posit is investing more in this new IDE, Positron, than in RStudio.

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:16.880
That is true. However, we expect people to use RStudio for many, many years

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:23.119
to come. We're committed to maintenance for RStudio in the long haul. If RStudio

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:29.679
meets your needs today, do not have FOMO. You should not feel any worry or

00:10:29.679 --> 00:10:33.640
anxiety about continuing to use it because it is going to continue to be

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:39.679
there for you. That's about Positron feeling familiar. Positron also feels

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:44.200
familiar to some of you who are listening to this because it's built on

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:50.440
the open-source components that make up Visual Studio Code. Positron is a

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:55.559
fork of the open-source project that Microsoft uses to make their

00:10:55.559 --> 00:11:00.599
proprietary builds of VS Code. This is an architectural decision that was

00:11:00.599 --> 00:11:07.440
made as we're exploring this idea of building a new IDE. Building on Code

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:15.000
OSS, as it is known, allows us to focus on the data science features, not the

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.320
sort of general features that all kinds of people who write code need.

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:24.440
Not, how do we make an editor where people can edit code? We don't have to

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:28.840
worry about that. We just kind of make a deal where we say, okay, we will accept

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:34.640
largely how things work in VS Code, and we add on top of that the things that

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:41.000
are specific about what someone doing statistical analysis needs. That

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:46.359
lets us focus on the kinds of things we have expertise in and that we want to be

00:11:46.359 --> 00:11:52.200
able to focus on. The other thing here is that building on Code OSS opens up the

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:58.599
wide world of VS Code compatible extensions for users who want a data

00:11:58.599 --> 00:12:03.799
science IDE instead of a general-purpose IDE. If you're coming from our studio,

00:12:03.799 --> 00:12:10.039
this ability to customize your IDE is new and may be a reason that you might

00:12:10.039 --> 00:12:15.679
want to try out Positron. Extensions exist for everything from

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:22.559
any theme you can possibly imagine to customize how it looks to support for

00:12:22.559 --> 00:12:28.479
data platforms that you want to access, like Databricks and Snowflakes.

00:12:28.479 --> 00:12:34.559
Actually, you also can build extensions yourself. The barrier to entry to

00:12:34.559 --> 00:12:40.159
building an extension is lower than what it would have taken to customize our

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:46.239
studio, for example, there. Now, when folks hear about extensions or if they

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:51.400
already know about extensions, sometimes those folks ask, why not just build

00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:57.919
extensions? Why not just, instead of forking the whole thing and making a new

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:03.880
thing, a new thing here, Positron, why not just build extensions that would allow

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:10.159
VS Code to be usable for data science? Now, we thought very carefully

00:13:10.159 --> 00:13:13.919
about that. We thought, think carefully about the features that are part of

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:20.280
Positron itself versus what we do with integration with extensions. So, we love

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:24.119
extensions. We make extensions. So, we at Posit have created and

00:13:24.119 --> 00:13:30.359
maintain extensions for Quarto, for Shiny, for Publishing, to Posit Connect.

00:13:30.359 --> 00:13:36.039
This screenshot shows that. Someone is mid-deployment, just in the process of

00:13:36.039 --> 00:13:42.039
publishing this Quarto dashboard to Posit Connect. We are all in on extensions,

00:13:42.039 --> 00:13:47.280
huge fans of the extension ecosystem. However, because we have learned about

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:52.239
extensions, we also know about the limits of what an extension can do and not

00:13:52.239 --> 00:13:58.119
everything that we believe we need for a first-class data science IDE can be

00:13:58.119 --> 00:14:03.599
built into extensions. So, we're all in, but we think very carefully about what

00:14:03.599 --> 00:14:08.760
goes in the core of Positron itself and what can be an extension. If you want to

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:15.440
think about it in a very shorthand, when we need more of the UI to be

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:20.320
integrated and connected, then it needs to be in the core of the product rather

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:26.479
than in an extension. Building on top of Code OSS, something else this lets us do

00:14:26.479 --> 00:14:31.359
is it gives us opportunities to provide functionality for our users that just

00:14:31.359 --> 00:14:35.799
has not been available to our studio users. So, one example of this is the

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:40.719
Test Explorer for R packages. So, this screenshot shows an R package

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:46.799
that I maintain, and what we see here is there's this rich UI for

00:14:46.799 --> 00:14:50.520
running and understanding your package tests, and this kind of thing has

00:14:50.520 --> 00:14:55.840
never been available in our studio. The way this works is that Code OSS provides

00:14:55.840 --> 00:15:01.919
the front end here, the UI, and then we build out a back end for how our

00:15:01.919 --> 00:15:07.200
packages get parsed and understood by this kind of UI that we have here.

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:11.919
Specifically for R packages, as someone who maintains a number of them myself,

00:15:11.919 --> 00:15:15.760
I'm really excited about what Positron offers to folks who are building these

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:22.000
packages that then get to be used by the whole R community. Now, if I'm here

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:27.559
on a video talking about a new IDE in 2025, I know one of the very first

00:15:27.559 --> 00:15:32.840
questions that a lot of you have is how and in what ways Positron is set up to

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:38.880
work with LLMs. So, like I mentioned before, Positron is not a general-purpose

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:44.000
software engineering IDE. So, if you are familiar with other forks of VS Code,

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:49.000
like Cursor and Windsurf, we don't see those as our direct competitors because

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.159
those are general-purpose software engineering IDEs. Instead, our goals are

00:15:54.159 --> 00:15:58.119
to build an IDE for data science specifically, something that is useful

00:15:58.119 --> 00:16:05.400
for statistical analysis. And how we think about AI integration and LLM code

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:09.599
assistance, it's deeply informed by this perspective on data science that

00:16:09.599 --> 00:16:14.840
we have. We want to ask, what do people doing statistical analysis need when it

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:20.840
comes to LLMs? What are the legitimately useful applications for LLMs in such an

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:25.760
IDE? I personally would make, if I were to make a list of that, of things that are

00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:32.479
legitimately useful today, one would be initial exploratory data analysis with

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:36.799
new data sets, just like that, like quick, like let's write a bunch of code to find

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:42.559
out what's in a data set. Another example that I think is legitimately useful

00:16:42.559 --> 00:16:49.599
today, generating test cases, like writing tests for, say, an R package,

00:16:49.599 --> 00:16:55.159
generating comments. Another thing is navigating and understanding a complex

00:16:55.159 --> 00:16:59.320
code base. That's another example that I think is legitimately useful for people,

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:05.520
for example, who use R today. So, we at Posit, we are not training new models,

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:12.640
but rather we're building tools on top of these classes of models and on top of

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:18.520
the model providers. So, in this IDE, in Positron, what that looks like is these

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:23.800
integrations, these IDE integrations. It looks like things like commands that you

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:29.439
can use in chat, chat participants that you can go on to make this very data

00:17:29.439 --> 00:17:38.760
science aware LLM integration. So, this screenshot shows me using Positron

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:42.520
Assistant, as it is known. So, the assistant is over there on one side. I've

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:46.880
got my console, and then I'm seeing the results of the code that the

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:51.280
assistant is running. So, Positron Assistant can be run in three modes, ask,

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:58.040
edit, and agent. Here, I'm using it in an agent mode, where I actually let the

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:04.439
assistant run code iteratively in the console, and both the assistant and I see

00:18:04.439 --> 00:18:10.280
the results. This is powerful because it is built for data science, because it is

00:18:10.280 --> 00:18:14.719
deeply integrated into the ideas as a whole. So, like, here is an example of

00:18:14.719 --> 00:18:19.239
something I typed here, where I say, oh, okay, that last plot you made,

00:18:19.239 --> 00:18:24.079
let's make that again. But this data set is about Pokemon from a recent

00:18:24.079 --> 00:18:28.680
Heidi Tuesday. It's like, okay, I want to, like, let me please make that plot again,

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:34.160
but with, like, a different variable. And then here is the assistant's response

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:38.959
here, where it generates code for me, and then I can click a button to run it in

00:18:38.959 --> 00:18:43.520
the console there. So, if you want to learn more about what the rise of these

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:48.719
models mean for our users, I would point you to the first keynote for UseR this

00:18:48.719 --> 00:18:56.560
year by Hadley Wickham about using AI in the R ecosystem. So, if you are

00:18:56.560 --> 00:19:02.719
interested now in trying out Positron, I would point you to positron.posit.co

00:19:02.719 --> 00:19:09.560
for documentation and installers. I would invite you to join us on GitHub with any

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:15.119
feedback that you have, questions, bug reports, et cetera. If you're a customer

00:19:15.119 --> 00:19:20.920
of Posit's, Positron is currently available on Posit Workbench in preview.

00:19:20.920 --> 00:19:23.599
And with that, I will say, thank you very much.

